Univariate plot section

From the plots, we can observe that, as count increases the fixed acidity content also increases and once count maxes out at roughly a value of 200, then goes on reducing as the fixed acidity content in the wine increases. In the plot of count vs density and ph, the plots almost have a normal distribution. We can see that at 0.1 quantity of chlorides the count value maxes out at a value of 775. Not much could be inferred from the plot between the quality and the count variables.

The boxplots depicting outliers for some features of the wine is shown below

From the plot, we can observe that for lower values of residual sugar the count value is exceptionally high. And it is evident that as the residual sugar content increases in the wine the count value decreases. And almost becomes zero for residual sugar values after 8.

With the absence of citric acid in the wine, the count value is at its maximum value. As the citric acid content increases, the count value does drop for sometimes, but at 0.50, the count value increases and subsequently goes on decreasing as the citric acidity value of the wine increases.

In the closed interval of [4,12] of fixed acidity, the count value is at its maximum, and is almost negligible for other value of fixed acidity in the wine sample.

This is a very surprising plot. We can see that for a very short closed interval of [0,1.75] the value of count is indeed very high. And is virtually nonexistent even for higher values of chlorides in the wine under consideration.

Univariate Analysis

Quality of wine

It is clearly evident that the wine quality range approximately falls between 3 and 8 with 5 and 6 being the most frequent ones. To deal with this we categorize the quality into three types, poor, good and best and create another variable called rating. 0 - 4: poor 5 - 6: good 7 - 10: best

Majority of the entries in the dataset fall under the good category. The best the category has a sizeable number of data values and the poor wine category has the least.

Summary of rating

## poor good best 
##   63 1319  217

As we can see, there are 39 data values which are classified as poor, 1319 as good wines and 217 as best wines in the given dataset.

Total acidity

create a new variable called total.acidity to calculate the sum of all acids.

## [1]  8.10  8.68  8.60 12.04  8.10  8.06

Here a variable total acidity is created to hold the values of summation of all acids present in the wine. The values can be seen above.

Distribution and Outliers

Fixed.acidity, Volatile.acidity, Sulfur.dioxide, Sulfates, and Alcohol appear to be long-tailed. Density and pH are normally distributed with few outliers. residual.sugar and chlorides have extreme outliers. Citric.acid contains a large number of zero values.

Find number of entries with zero values in citric.acid

It is evident that 132 entries for citric acid have the value zero.

Visualize patterns in chlorides after removing outliers

Bivariate Analysis

Poor rating seems to have following trends:

lower fixed.acidity, higher volatile.acidity and lower citric.acid lower sulfur.dioxide and sulfates, higher pH and high density

Good rating seems to have following trends:

low fixed.acidity and volatile.acidity higher sulfur.dioxide low pH and higher density

Best rating seems to have following trends:

higher fixed.Acidity, lower volatile.acidity and higher citric.acid low sulfur.dioxide and higher sulfates lower pH and density

Let’s see some relationships between some variable and total.acidity

We see that there is almost a linear relationship between density and log10(total.acidity), and pH and log10(total.acidity). The plot between density and total acidity has a positive slope while that of ph vs total acidity has a negative slope.

Multivariate Plots Section

I chose to plot alcohol percentage vs pH, because, pH governs many elements in winemaking and is consequently a crucial parameter. One important effect of pH, concerns wine stability - very simple adverse organism are far less able to survive in wine that contains strong acidity as a result low pH. Majority of pH values are in the good wine category roughly between 3.0 and 4.0 quality factors.

Usually citric acid content in the wine needs to be less, otherwise, the wine may become aggressively citric in nature. It is always added after alcohol fermentation as yeasts convert it into acetic acid.

Sulphates play a very important role in the art of winemaking, due to its ability to maintain the freshness of the wine for a long duration. The plot of sulfates and alcohol % reveal that majority of the data points are indeed concentrated for the good category wine. The alcohol percentage has a quality factor between 9 and 13 for the good category wine, which is the most populous.

Since, by convention total.acidity is of two types, volatile and fixed acids. I wanted to visualize the relations between fixed and citric acids. From the plot it is evident that even at 0 quality factor for citric acids te fixed acids are the majority in number for the good category wines.

Multivariate Analysis

I plotted a graph between four variables citric.acid, fixed.acidity, sulfates and alcohol which shown high correlations with quality and faceted them with the rating. I conclude that higher citric.acid and lower fixed.acidity yields better wines. Better wines also have higher alcohol and sulfates and lower pH.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One: Effect of alcohol on wine quality

Description One

We can observe from the plot that, since alcohol is highly correlated with quality, it is better to see its pattern with varying rating.We can observe from the plot that, higher the percentage of alcohol better is the wine quality.

Plot Two: Effect of acids on wine quality

Description Two

We can deduce from the plot that as the acidity increases the quality of the wine too increases. From the plot, we can observe different impacts of different acidities, fixed.acidity and citric.acid highly correlate with quality but the same is not true for volatile.acidity

Plot Three: poor vs best wine

Description Three

Higher the percentage of alcohol and higher sulfates give better quality wines which we can see from that plot that they are directly proportional to each other.

Even those in excess cause a negative the effect, hence they also should have a constraint. I am not so confident of the quality index and not much information is available. From the plots, there is (slope -ve)linear relationship between pH and wine quality.I was unable to get a correct picture of residual.sugar. It contains numerous outliers and after cleaning data I bound its range between 1 to 4. But I was unable to get the amount in which it is to be present to make the wine quality ideal. More exploring and analysis needs to be done in this regard to get a clearer picture.
